Part I - Ford GoBike System Data Exploration and Visualization¶

By Wejdan Al-Qahtani¶

Introduction¶

In the San Francisco Bay Area of California, Ford GoBike is a regional public bicycle sharing scheme. Bay Area Bike Share, a pilot program for the region, started in August 2013 with 700 bikes and 70 stations dispersed around San Francisco and San Jose. The Ford GoBike system presently has more than 2,600 bicycles spread out among 262 stations in San Francisco, the East Bay, and San Jose. On June 28, 2017, the program was formally unveiled as Ford GoBike in collaboration with Ford Motor Company.¶

The Ford GoBike bike share program uses a fleet of strong, well-made bikes that are locked into a system of docking stations spread out over the city. The bike is perfect for one-way travels because you may unlock it at one station and return it to any other station in the network. Additionally, the bikes are always ready for use, and anyone can use any bike in the network provided they join or buy a pass.¶

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

Approximately 1,860,000 unique trip records with 16 variables were obtained in the original merged data.

>

Three broad groups can be made from the variables:

>

station info: start_station_id, start_station_name, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitudetrip duration: duration_sec, start_time, end_time

*member informations (anonymized): bike_id, user_type, member_birth_year, member_gender, bike_share_for_all_trip

Derived variables for analysis and exploration:

*trip info: duration_minute, start_date, start_hourofday, start_dayofweek, start_month

  • member: member_age

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

In order to gain a better understanding of how and why people use the bike sharing service, I became interested in examining the length of bike trips and the frequency of rental events, as well as how they might relate to the riders' characteristics, such as by the user type, gender, and age. In order to answer a few questions such as: How long does a typical trip last? When, in terms of a day, a day of the week, or weeks in a month, are most journeys taken? Does the aforementioned depend on a user's membership or client status?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I'll be able to estimate how long and when a trip generally lasts by using the start/end times and length details for each journey. Using member information such as user type, gender, and age, where I can determine the main target customer groups. I can then use the various categories to summarize data on bike usage and search for any unusual patterns relating to a certain group of riders.

Subscribers use is far higher than consumer usage. Customers and subscribers have quite different riding habits and patterns. Most trips on work days (Mon-Fri) and especially during rush hours (when going to work in the morning and getting off work in the afternoon) were made by subscribers because they use the bike sharing system for commuting, whereas customers typically ride for fun in the afternoon or early evening on weekends. The average ride length is somewhat longer for subscriber users than for consumer users, especially in the summer.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Conclusions¶

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

The relationship between the various variables plotted is seen collectively and information is displayed simultaneously, strengthening some of the patterns identified in the preceding bivariate investigation as well as in the univariate research. Subscribers' efficient/short periods of consumption are consistent with their high concentration during Monday through Friday rush hours, showing that the use is mostly for commuting to work. Customers clearly utilize the bike sharing system considerably differently than subscribers, frequently on weekends and in the afternoons, likely for leisure or city tours, as seen by the more flexible and relaxing pattern of their usage.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

When features interact with one another and make sense when seen as a whole, there is little to surprise about. Because there are disproportionately more female riders and records than male ones, the usage habits of men and women are not as different or visible throughout the investigation. If there were more female data, it would be interesting to observe how male and female users of the system varied from one another.
